{
  "texts": [
    "Since the linear space I(P d) separates points of P d (by definition), it is weak * dense in (P d) * by the bipolar theorem [13, Chapter 5, 1.8].",
    "Thus, I is surjective if and only I(P d) is weak * closed.",
    "By the Kreǐn-Shmul'yan theorem [13,Chapter 5,12.1], this is the case if and only if I(P d) ∩ λB P d is weak * closed for any λ ≥ 0.",
    "Since P d is separable, the weak * topology restricted to any ball is metrisable and hence by the Banach-Alaoglu theorem, the above is equivalent to requiring that I(P d) ∩ λB P d be sequentially weak * compact.We now show the implication (i) =⇒ (ii).",
    "Since I is bounded, the sequence I(ω j) is bounded in (P d) *, say it lies in λB (P d) *, therefore it has a weak * convergent subsequence I(ω j k) → Φ ∈ λB (P d) *."
  ]
}